00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:06,000
In plain English, this command asks AWS "who am I?"

192
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:12,000
The output should look something like this.

193
00:19:12,000 --> 00:19:18,000
A UserId, an Account number, and an ARN.

194
00:19:18,000 --> 00:19:24,000
The most important field here is Account.
That 12-digit number is your AWS account ID. Write it down.

195
00:19:24,000 --> 00:19:30,000
You'll need it.

196
00:19:30,000 --> 00:19:36,000
If you see your account ID, you're ready.
The AWS CLI is installed correctly.

197
00:19:36,000 --> 00:19:42,000
Your credentials are configured. You have access.

198
00:19:42,000 --> 00:19:48,000
Troubleshooting.
If you get an error that says "Unable to locate credentials".

199
00:19:48,000 --> 00:19:54,000
That means you haven't configured the AWS CLI yet.
Run aws configure and enter your Access Key ID,
Secret Access Key, default region, and default output format.

200
00:19:54,000 --> 00:20:00,000
You can get your Access Key ID and Secret Access Key
from the AWS console under IAM > Users > Security credentials.

201
00:20:00,000 --> 00:20:06,000
If you get an error that says "Access denied".

202
00:20:06,000 --> 00:20:12,000
That means your credentials exist but don't have permission
to call this API.

203
00:20:12,000 --> 00:20:18,000
You need at least read access to Cost Explorer and EC2
for this course.

204
00:20:18,000 --> 00:20:24,000
For now, I recommend attaching the AWSBillingReadOnlyAccess
and AmazonEC2ReadOnlyAccess managed policies to your IAM user.

205
00:20:24,000 --> 00:20:30,000
You can do this in the AWS console under IAM > Users >
Add permissions.

206
00:20:30,000 --> 00:20:36,000
Once you see your account ID, export these environment variables.

207
00:20:36,000 --> 00:20:42,000
Environment variables are like global settings
that every command can see.

208
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:48,000
You set them once at the beginning of your session
and every command after that can use them.

209
00:20:48,000 --> 00:20:54,000
export ACCOUNT_ID equals aws sts get-caller-identity
with query Account output text.

210
00:20:54,000 --> 00:21:00,000
export REGION equals us-east-1.
export START equals date minus d 30 days ago plus YYYY-MM-DD.

211
00:21:00,000 --> 00:21:06,000
export END equals date plus YYYY-MM-DD.

212
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:12,000
Important note for macOS users.
The date command on macOS is different.

213
00:21:12,000 --> 00:21:18,000
Instead of date minus d 30 days ago,
use date minus v minus 30d.

214
00:21:18,000 --> 00:21:24,000
Let me explain each one.

215
00:21:24,000 --> 00:21:30,000
ACCOUNT_ID is your AWS account ID.
We're using a subshell trick here.

216
00:21:30,000 --> 00:21:36,000
The dollar sign parentheses syntax runs the command
inside the parentheses and substitutes its output.

217
00:21:36,000 --> 00:21:42,000
REGION is the AWS region you're working in.
us-east-1 is Northern Virginia.

218
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:48,000
If your resources are in a different region, change this.

219
00:21:48,000 --> 00:21:54,000
START is the beginning of your cost lookback period.
We're using date dash d 30 days ago.

220
00:21:54,000 --> 00:22:00,000
Which calculates the date 30 days before today.

221
00:22:00,000 --> 00:22:06,000
END is today's date in the same format.

222
00:22:06,000 --> 00:22:12,000
Now verify that these variables are set correctly.

223
00:22:12,000 --> 00:22:18,000
echo dollar sign ACCOUNT_ID.
echo dollar sign REGION.

224
00:22:18,000 --> 00:22:24,000
echo dollar sign START.
echo dollar sign END.

225
00:22:24,000 --> 00:22:30,000
You should see your account ID, your region, and two dates.

226
00:22:30,000 --> 00:22:36,000
Now let's verify Cost Explorer access.
Run this command.

227
00:22:36,000 --> 00:22:42,000
aws ce get-cost-and-usage with time period
Start equals START, End equals END.

228
00:22:42,000 --> 00:22:48,000
Granularity MONTHLY, metrics BlendedCost.
Query results by time zero total blended cost amount.

229
00:22:48,000 --> 00:22:54,000
Output text.

230
00:22:54,000 --> 00:23:00,000
This command returns your total spend for the last 30 days.
If you see a number, even if it's zero, you have Cost Explorer access.

231
00:23:00,000 --> 00:23:06,000
Write this number down. It's your baseline.
This is the number you're going to reduce over the next 10 series.

232
00:23:06,000 --> 00:23:12,000
Troubleshooting.
If you get an error that says "Invalid time period".

233
00:23:12,000 --> 00:23:18,000
Check that your START and END variables are set correctly.
Run echo dollar sign START and echo dollar sign END.

234
00:23:18,000 --> 00:23:24,000
They should be dates in YYYY-MM-DD format.

235
00:23:24,000 --> 00:23:30,000
If you get an error that says "Access denied"
or "Unauthorized operation".

236
00:23:30,000 --> 00:23:36,000
Your IAM user doesn't have permission to call Cost Explorer.
Go back to the AWS console and add the AWSBillingReadOnlyAccess
policy.

237
00:23:36,000 --> 00:23:42,000
Now you're ready for unit economics.

238
00:23:42,000 --> 00:23:48,000
Now let me show you what unit economics actually means.

239
00:23:48,000 --> 00:23:54,000
Because this is the concept that separates
senior engineers from junior engineers.

240
00:23:54,000 --> 00:24:00,000
Senior engineers talk about unit economics.
Junior engineers talk about the AWS bill.

241
00:24:00,000 --> 00:24:06,000
In simple terms, unit economics is the answer
to one question.

242
00:24:06,000 --> 00:24:12,000
What does one unit of your business cost?

243
00:24:12,000 --> 00:24:18,000
If you're running a RAG application,
the unit is one RAG query.

244
00:24:18,000 --> 00:24:24,000
A user asks a question. The system retrieves
relevant documents.

245
00:24:24,000 --> 00:24:30,000
The language model generates an answer.
That whole process from question to answer is one unit.

246
00:24:30,000 --> 00:24:36,000
If you're running an API, the unit is one API call.
A client sends a request. The server processes it.

247
00:24:36,000 --> 00:24:42,000
The server sends a response.
That round trip is one unit.

248
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:48,000
If you're running a batch job, the unit is one job execution.
The job starts. It processes data.

249
00:24:48,000 --> 00:24:54,000
It writes results. It finishes.
That complete execution is one unit.

250
00:24:54,000 --> 00:25:00,000
Here's why this matters.
Most engineering teams look at their AWS bill
and see $47,832.45.

251
00:25:00,000 --> 00:25:06,000
That number is useless.
It doesn't tell you if you're efficient.

252
00:25:06,000 --> 00:25:12,000
It doesn't tell you if that new feature you shipped
made things better or worse.

253
00:25:12,000 --> 00:25:18,000
It doesn't tell you if you're spending too much
or too little. It's just a number.

254
00:25:18,000 --> 00:25:24,000
But if you know that one RAG query costs $0.002,
that's two-tenths of a cent. Now you have something.

255
00:25:24,000 --> 00:25:30,000
Now you can do math.

256
00:25:30,000 --> 00:25:36,000
You can answer. We processed two million queries this month.
At $0.002 each, that's $4,000.

257
00:25:36,000 --> 00:25:42,000
Our total bill is $12,000.
Where is the other $8,000 going?

258
00:25:42,000 --> 00:25:48,000
That question is the beginning of FinOps.
That question leads you to investigate.

259
00:25:48,000 --> 00:25:54,000
You look at the breakdown by service.
You see that NAT Gateway is costing you $2,000.

260
00:25:54,000 --> 00:26:00,000
You see that you have five unattached Elastic IPs
costing you $18.

261
00:26:00,000 --> 00:26:06,000
You see that you have stopped instances
with EBS volumes costing you $300.

262
00:26:06,000 --> 00:26:12,000
Now you have a plan.
Now you know exactly what to fix and in what order.

263
00:26:12,000 --> 00:26:18,000
That's the power of unit economics.

264
00:26:18,000 --> 00:26:24,000
Write this formula down.
Cost per unit equals total monthly infrastructure cost
divided by number of units processed.

265
00:26:24,000 --> 00:26:30,000
For financial-rag-agent, your unit is a RAG query.
For riskoracle, your unit is a risk calculation.

266
00:26:30,000 --> 00:26:36,000
By the end of this course, you will have both numbers.
And you will know exactly how to improve them.

267
00:26:36,000 --> 00:26:42,000
Now let me walk you through a real example
from an actual deployment of financial-rag-agent.

268
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:48,000
This client processes about 500,000 RAG queries per month.
That's about 16,000 queries per day.

269
00:26:48,000 --> 00:26:54,000
That's about 11 queries per minute.
It's a moderately busy system.

270
00:26:54,000 --> 00:27:00,000
Not huge, but not tiny either.

271
00:27:00,000 --> 00:27:06,000
Their total AWS bill is $8,400 per month.

272
00:27:06,000 --> 00:27:12,000
Let me calculate their cost per query.
Total cost divided by total queries.

273
00:27:12,000 --> 00:27:18,000
$8,400 divided by 500,000 equals $0.0168 per query.
That's 1.68 cents per query.

274
00:27:18,000 --> 00:27:24,000
Let me break down where that 1.68 cents per query goes.
This is the detail that most people never see.

275
00:27:24,000 --> 00:27:30,000
Here is the cost breakdown per query table.

276
00:27:30,000 --> 00:27:36,000
EC2 compute for LLM inference: 0.8 cents per query.
48 percent of the total.

277
00:27:36,000 --> 00:27:42,000
RDS for the vector database: 0.3 cents per query.
18 percent of the total.

278
00:27:42,000 --> 00:27:48,000
NAT Gateway plus data transfer: 0.2 cents per query.
12 percent of the total.

279
00:27:48,000 --> 00:27:54,000
EKS control plane: 0.2 cents per query.
12 percent of the total.

280
00:27:54,000 --> 00:28:00,000
S3 for document storage: 0.1 cents per query.
6 percent of the total.

281
00:28:00,000 --> 00:28:06,000
Other services like CloudWatch and ECR: 0.08 cents per query.
4 percent of the total.

282
00:28:06,000 --> 00:28:12,000
The large language model that generates answers
runs on GPU instances. GPUs are expensive.

283
00:28:12,000 --> 00:28:18,000
This is the biggest line item at 48 percent.

284
00:28:18,000 --> 00:28:24,000
Is 1.68 cents good or bad?
It depends on what you charge.

285
00:28:24,000 --> 00:28:30,000
If they're charging their customers 10 cents per query,
their cost is 1.68 cents.

286
00:28:30,000 --> 00:28:36,000
Their margin is 8.32 cents per query.
That's an 83% margin. That's great.

287
00:28:36,000 --> 00:28:42,000
If they're charging their customers 2 cents per query,
their cost is 1.68 cents.

288
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:48,000
Their margin is 0.32 cents per query.
That's a 16% margin.

289
00:28:48,000 --> 00:28:54,000
They're barely breaking even.
One small mistake and they're losing money.

290
00:28:54,000 --> 00:29:00,000
Now look at the biggest line item.
EC2 compute at 48 percent.

291
00:29:00,000 --> 00:29:06,000
That's where Karpenter and Spot instances
will have the biggest impact.

292
00:29:06,000 --> 00:29:12,000
If you can reduce EC2 cost by 35 percent using
Karpenter consolidation, that reduces the total cost per query
from 1.68 cents to 1.42 cents.

293
00:29:12,000 --> 00:29:18,000
If you can run some workloads on Spot instances
at 70 percent off, that reduces the total even further.

294
00:29:18,000 --> 00:29:24,000
If you can eliminate NAT Gateway costs entirely
using VPC endpoints, that's another 12 percent reduction.

295
00:29:24,000 --> 00:29:30,000
After implementing all the optimizations in this course,
that client reduced their cost per query to 0.98 cents.

296
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:36,000
That's a 42 percent reduction.
Their margin at 10 cents per query went from 83 percent to 90 percent.

297
00:29:36,000 --> 00:29:42,000
That's the difference between a startup that survives
and a startup that thrives.

298
00:29:42,000 --> 00:29:48,000
Now let me show you why this number matters
to your CTO.

299
00:29:48,000 --> 00:29:54,000
Your CTO cares about two things.
Shipping features and not running out of money.

300
00:29:54,000 --> 00:30:00,000
Unit economics is the bridge between them.

301
00:30:00,000 --> 00:30:06,000
Here's the conversation you can have after this course.

302
00:30:06,000 --> 00:30:12,000
You walk into the CTO's office.
You say, "Our cost per RAG query is 1.68 cents."

303
00:30:12,000 --> 00:30:18,000
The CTO looks at you. "Is that good?" they ask.
You say, "It's okay. But I can get it to 0.9 cents
by next quarter."

304
00:30:18,000 --> 00:30:24,000
The CTO leans forward. "How?"
You say, "Karpenter consolidation on EKS will cut EC2 cost
by 35 percent."

305
00:30:24,000 --> 00:30:30,000
"Spot instances for batch processing will save
another 15 percent. VPC endpoints eliminate NAT Gateway costs
entirely."

306
00:30:30,000 --> 00:30:36,000
"And I'm going to bake cost visibility into the IDP
so every team sees their impact before they deploy."

307
00:30:36,000 --> 00:30:42,000
The CTO says, "Do it."

308
00:30:42,000 --> 00:30:48,000
That's the conversation. Not "we need to save money."
Not "cloud is too expensive."

309
00:30:48,000 --> 00:30:54,000
Just data, a plan, and a number.
That's what unit economics gives you.

310
00:30:54,000 --> 00:31:00,000
Now let me show you how to calculate this for yourself.

311
00:31:00,000 --> 00:31:06,000
First, get your total monthly cost.
You already have this from the verification step.

312
00:31:06,000 --> 00:31:12,000
TOTAL_COST equals aws ce get-cost-and-usage with time period
Start END granularity MONTHLY metrics BlendedCost.

313
00:31:12,000 --> 00:31:18,000
Query results by time zero total blended cost amount.
Output text.

314
00:31:18,000 --> 00:31:24,000
echo "Total monthly AWS cost: dollar sign TOTAL_COST"

315
00:31:24,000 --> 00:31:30,000
Second, get your total number of RAG queries.
This assumes you're logging each query to CloudWatch.

316
00:31:30,000 --> 00:31:36,000
If you're not, we'll set this up in Series 8
when we build the IDP.

317
00:31:36,000 --> 00:31:42,000
TOTAL_QUERIES equals aws cloudwatch get-metric-statistics
with namespace financial-rag-agent.

318
00:31:42,000 --> 00:31:48,000
Metric name QueryCount. Start time START T 00:00:00Z.
End time END T 00:00:00Z.

319
00:31:48,000 --> 00:31:54,000
Period 2592000. Statistics Sum.
Query datapoints zero sum. Output text.

320
00:31:54,000 --> 00:32:00,000
echo "Total monthly RAG queries: dollar sign TOTAL_QUERIES"

321
00:32:00,000 --> 00:32:06,000
Third, calculate the cost per query.

322
00:32:06,000 --> 00:32:12,000
echo "Cost per RAG query: " with scale 6 and TOTAL_COST divided by TOTAL_QUERIES using bc.

323
00:32:12,000 --> 00:32:18,000
If you don't have CloudWatch metrics set up yet,
don't worry. We'll add them in Series 8.

324
00:32:18,000 --> 00:32:24,000
For now, just understand the concept.
Because every decision you make in this course.

325
00:32:24,000 --> 00:32:30,000
Every rightsizing, every Karpenter consolidation,
every Spot instance, every VPC endpoint.

326
00:32:30,000 --> 00:32:36,000
Should be evaluated against this number.
Does this change reduce cost per query?

327
00:32:36,000 --> 00:32:42,000
If yes, do it. If no, ask why.
That's how senior engineers think about cloud cost.

328
00:32:42,000 --> 00:32:48,000
Now let's talk about the mechanism that makes
unit economics possible.

329
00:32:48,000 --> 00:32:54,000
The thing that lets you break down your total bill
into cost per team, cost per service, cost per environment.

330
00:32:54,000 --> 00:33:00,000
That mechanism is tagging.

331
00:33:00,000 --> 00:33:06,000
Now let's talk about tagging.
Tags are labels that you attach to AWS resources.

332
00:33:06,000 --> 00:33:12,000
A tag is a key-value pair. The key is something like Environment.
The value is something like production.

333
00:33:12,000 --> 00:33:18,000
So you tag an EC2 instance with Environment equals production.
You tag an S3 bucket with Team equals financial-rag.

334
00:33:18,000 --> 00:33:24,000
You tag an RDS database with CostCenter equals engineering.

335
00:33:24,000 --> 00:33:30,000
Here's the hard truth.
Without tags, you have no idea who spent what.

336
00:33:30,000 --> 00:33:36,000
Without tags, you are flying blind.

337
00:33:36,000 --> 00:33:42,000
Cost Explorer shows you EC2 cost.
But which team spun up those instances?

338
00:33:42,000 --> 00:33:48,000
Was it the financial-rag team or the riskoracle team?
You don't know.

339
00:33:48,000 --> 00:33:54,000
Cost Explorer shows you S3 cost.
But which service is generating all that data transfer?

340
00:33:54,000 --> 00:34:00,000
Is it the LLM ingest service or the batch processing job?
You don't know.

341
00:34:00,000 --> 00:34:06,000
Tags answer those questions.
Tags give you the dimensions you need to break down your bill.

342
00:34:06,000 --> 00:34:12,000
Tags are how you move from total spend
to cost per team, cost per service, cost per environment.

343
00:34:12,000 --> 00:34:18,000
Here's the tagging standard I use on every engagement.
I've used this at over 50 startups.

344
00:34:18,000 --> 00:34:24,000
It works. It scales.
It's simple enough that everyone remembers it.

345
00:34:24,000 --> 00:34:30,000
And comprehensive enough that you never find yourself
missing a dimension.

346
00:34:30,000 --> 00:34:36,000
You are going to apply these six tags
to every resource in your account.
No exceptions.

347
00:34:36,000 --> 00:34:42,000
Here is the six tags table.

348
00:34:42,000 --> 00:34:48,000
Tag key: Environment. Example values: production, staging,
development, test. Purpose: Separate prod spend from test spend.

349
00:34:48,000 --> 00:34:54,000
Tag key: Team. Example values: financial-rag, riskoracle,
platform. Purpose: Chargeback. Show each team their cost.

350
00:34:54,000 --> 00:35:00,000
Tag key: Service. Example values: llm-ingest, risk-calc,
api-gateway. Purpose: Granular attribution per microservice.

351
00:35:00,000 --> 00:35:06,000
Tag key: ManagedBy. Example values: terraform, kubecost,
manual. Purpose: Know who created and how to manage it.

352
00:35:06,000 --> 00:35:12,000
Tag key: CostCenter. Example values: engineering,
data-science, product. Purpose: Roll up to your finance department.

353
00:35:12,000 --> 00:35:18,000
Tag key: Owner. Example value: aayo at company.com.
Purpose: The person responsible. Who to ping.

354
00:35:18,000 --> 00:35:24,000
The golden rule.
Every resource gets every tag. No exceptions.

355
00:35:24,000 --> 00:35:30,000
Not some resources. Not most resources. Every resource.
EC2 instances, EBS volumes, RDS databases, S3 buckets.

356
00:35:30,000 --> 00:35:36,000
Load balancers, Lambda functions, EKS clusters, everything.

357
00:35:36,000 --> 00:35:42,000
Why so strict? Because the moment you allow
one untagged resource, you lose the ability
to trust your data.

358
00:35:42,000 --> 00:35:48,000
Is that $500 of EC2 cost untagged
because it's shared infrastructure that belongs to everyone?

359
00:35:48,000 --> 00:35:54,000
Or is it untagged because someone forgot?
You don't know.

360
00:35:54,000 --> 00:36:00,000
And now your unit economics are wrong.
Now you can't trust your cost per team report.

361
00:36:00,000 --> 00:36:06,000
Now you have to manually investigate every discrepancy.

362
00:36:06,000 --> 00:36:12,000
Trust me. I've seen this happen.
A startup tags 99 percent of their resources.
They feel good about themselves.

363
00:36:12,000 --> 00:36:18,000
They run a cost by team report. It looks great.
Then they discover that the 1 percent of untagged resources
accounts for 20 percent of their spend.

364
00:36:18,000 --> 00:36:24,000
Their report was wrong. Their decisions were based
on wrong data.

365
00:36:24,000 --> 00:36:30,000
They wasted weeks optimizing the wrong things.
Enforce the six tags. Enforce them strictly.

366
00:36:30,000 --> 00:36:36,000
Enforce them from day one.

367
00:36:36,000 --> 00:36:42,000
Now let me show you how to enforce them.

368
00:36:42,000 --> 00:36:48,000
Step 1. Activate Tags for Cost Allocation.
First, let's see what tags you already have active
in your account for cost allocation.

369
00:36:48,000 --> 00:36:54,000
Cost Explorer can only group by tags that are activated.
aws ce list-cost-allocation-tags with status Active.

370
00:36:54,000 --> 00:37:00,000
Output table.

371
00:37:00,000 --> 00:37:06,000
This shows you every tag that Cost Explorer knows about.
If your six tags aren't here, you need to activate them.

372
00:37:06,000 --> 00:37:12,000
The command to activate a tag is.
aws ce update-cost-allocation-tags-status with tags Team
status Active.

373
00:37:12,000 --> 00:37:18,000
Do this for each of the six tags.
Environment, Team, Service, ManagedBy, CostCenter, Owner.

374
00:37:18,000 --> 00:37:24,000
Step 2. Find Untagged EC2 Instances.
Now let's find resources with no tags at all.
Start with EC2 instances.

375
00:37:24,000 --> 00:37:30,000
aws ec2 describe-instances with query reservations
instances where tags length is zero.

376
00:37:30,000 --> 00:37:36,000
Show ID, Type, State. Output table.

377
00:37:36,000 --> 00:37:42,000
If this returns more than three rows, your cost allocation is broken.
Each row is an untagged EC2 instance.

378
00:37:42,000 --> 00:37:48,000
Each instance is a blind spot in your cost visibility.

379
00:37:48,000 --> 00:37:54,000
Step 3. Find Untagged S3 Buckets.
Now S3 buckets.

380
00:37:54,000 --> 00:38:00,000
aws s3api list-buckets query buckets name output text.
Pipe to while loop.

381
00:38:00,000 --> 00:38:06,000
For each bucket, get bucket tagging.
If tag set length is zero or null, print UNTAGGED S3 BUCKET.

382
00:38:06,000 --> 00:38:12,000
This loops through every S3 bucket in your account.
For each bucket, it tries to get the tags.

383
00:38:12,000 --> 00:38:18,000
If there are no tags, it prints the bucket name.
The 2 greater than dev null suppresses error messages.

384
00:38:18,000 --> 00:38:24,000
For buckets that have no tagging at all.

385
00:38:24,000 --> 00:38:30,000
Step 4. Find Untagged EBS Volumes.
Now EBS volumes.

386
00:38:30,000 --> 00:38:36,000
aws ec2 describe-volumes query volumes where tags length zero.
Show ID, Size, Type. Output table.

387
00:38:36,000 --> 00:38:42,000
Step 5. Find Untagged RDS Instances.
Now RDS instances.

388
00:38:42,000 --> 00:38:48,000
aws rds describe-db-instances query DBInstances
where tag list length zero.

389
00:38:48,000 --> 00:38:54,000
Show ID, Class, Engine. Output table.

390
00:38:54,000 --> 00:39:00,000
Step 6. Find Untagged Load Balancers.
Now load balancers.

391
00:39:00,000 --> 00:39:06,000
aws elbv2 describe-load-balancers query LoadBalancers
where tags length zero.

392
00:39:06,000 --> 00:39:12,000
Show Name, Type, State. Output table.

393
00:39:12,000 --> 00:39:18,000
Run all of these commands. Save the output.
This is your untagged inventory.

394
00:39:18,000 --> 00:39:24,000
This is the list of resources that are currently invisible
to your cost allocation.

395
00:39:24,000 --> 00:39:30,000
Now let's fix them.

396
00:39:30,000 --> 00:39:36,000
Here's how to tag a single EC2 instance
with all six tags.

397
00:39:36,000 --> 00:39:42,000
aws ec2 create-tags with resources i-1234567890abcdef0.

398
00:39:42,000 --> 00:39:48,000
Tags Key=Environment,Value=production
Key=Team,Value=financial-rag Key=Service,Value=llm-ingest.

399
00:39:48,000 --> 00:39:54,000
Key=ManagedBy,Value=terraform Key=CostCenter,Value=engineering
Key=Owner,Value=aayo at finops.com.

400
00:39:54,000 --> 00:40:00,000
The create-tags command takes a list of resources
and a list of tags.

401
00:40:00,000 --> 00:40:06,000
Each tag is a key-value pair.
You can tag up to 20 resources at once.

402
00:40:06,000 --> 00:40:12,000
You can add up to 50 tags per resource.

403
00:40:12,000 --> 00:40:18,000
But you don't want to do this one by one.
You have dozens or hundreds of resources.

404
00:40:18,000 --> 00:40:24,000
You need a bulk tagging script.

405
00:40:24,000 --> 00:40:30,000
Here's the complete bulk tagging script
that tags every EC2 instance in your account
with baseline tags.

406
00:40:30,000 --> 00:40:36,000
aws ec2 describe-instances query instances instance ID
output text.

407
00:40:36,000 --> 00:40:42,000
Pipe to while loop. For each ID, run create-tags
with the six required tags.

408
00:40:42,000 --> 00:40:48,000
Environment production. Team unknown.
Service unknown. ManagedBy finops.

409
00:40:48,000 --> 00:40:54,000
CostCenter engineering. Owner finops at yourcompany.com.
Echo "Tagged EC2: ID".

410
00:40:54,000 --> 00:41:00,000
This does several things. First, it gets a list
of all EC2 instance IDs.

411
00:41:00,000 --> 00:41:06,000
The query extracts just the IDs.
The output text formats them as plain text.

412
00:41:06,000 --> 00:41:12,000
The tr converts tabs to newlines so each ID
is on its own line.

413
00:41:12,000 --> 00:41:18,000
Then the while loop reads each ID
and runs the create-tags command.

414
00:41:18,000 --> 00:41:24,000
The tags are set to baseline values.
Environment is production. Team and Service are unknown.

415
00:41:24,000 --> 00:41:30,000
Because you need to fill those in manually.
ManagedBy is finops because you're the one tagging them.

416
00:41:30,000 --> 00:41:36,000
CostCenter is engineering. Owner is your FinOps email address.

417
00:41:36,000 --> 00:41:42,000
After this script runs, every EC2 instance has the six tags.
Then you go back and change the unknown values
to the real team and service names.

418
00:41:42,000 --> 00:41:48,000
Now let's do the same for EBS volumes.

419
00:41:48,000 --> 00:41:54,000
aws ec2 describe-volumes query volumes volume ID output text.
Pipe to while loop. For each ID, run create-tags.

420
00:41:54,000 --> 00:42:00,000
Same tags. Echo "Tagged EBS: ID".

421
00:42:00,000 --> 00:42:06,000
Now for RDS instances. Note that RDS uses a different command.
add-tags-to-resource instead of create-tags.

422
00:42:06,000 --> 00:42:12,000
And the resource identifier is an ARN, not just an ID.

423
00:42:12,000 --> 00:42:18,000
aws rds describe-db-instances query instances ARN output text.
Pipe to while loop. For each ARN, run add-tags-to-resource.

424
00:42:18,000 --> 00:42:24,000
Same tags. Echo "Tagged RDS: ARN".

425
00:42:24,000 --> 00:42:30,000
Now for load balancers.

426
00:42:30,000 --> 00:42:36,000
aws elbv2 describe-load-balancers query load balancer ARN
output text. Pipe to while loop.

427
00:42:36,000 --> 00:42:42,000
For each ARN, run add-tags with the same tags.
Echo "Tagged ALB: ARN".

428
00:42:42,000 --> 00:42:48,000
After you run all of these scripts,
every resource in your account has baseline tags.

429
00:42:48,000 --> 00:42:54,000
Now you need to go back and fill in the real team
and service names.

430
00:42:54,000 --> 00:43:00,000
You can do this manually or you can write a script
that updates based on instance names or other metadata.

431
00:43:00,000 --> 00:43:06,000
Now let's talk about preventing untagged resources
from being created in the future.

432
00:43:06,000 --> 00:43:12,000
Because tagging everything retroactively is painful.
It's much better to never create an untagged resource
in the first place.

433
00:43:12,000 --> 00:43:18,000
AWS Config is the service that continuously monitors
your resources for compliance.

434
00:43:18,000 --> 00:43:24,000
You can create rules that flag any resource
missing required tags.

435
00:43:24,000 --> 00:43:30,000
You can even block non-compliant resources
from being created.

436
00:43:30,000 --> 00:43:36,000
Here's the Config rule for our six required tags.

437
00:43:36,000 --> 00:43:42,000
aws configservice put-config-rule with config rule name
finops-required-tags.

438
00:43:42,000 --> 00:43:48,000
Description "Enforces six required tags on all resources".
Source Owner AWS, SourceIdentifier REQUIRED_TAGS.

439
00:43:48,000 --> 00:43:54,000
Input parameters with tag1Key Environment, tag2Key Team,
tag3Key Service, tag4Key ManagedBy, tag5Key CostCenter, tag6Key Owner.

440
00:43:54,000 --> 00:44:00,000
Scope with compliance resource types
AWS::EC2::Instance, AWS::EC2::Volume, AWS::RDS::DBInstance,
AWS::S3::Bucket, AWS::ElasticLoadBalancingV2::LoadBalancer.

441
00:44:00,000 --> 00:44:06,000
This rule checks every EC2 instance, EBS volume,
RDS instance, S3 bucket, and load balancer.

442
00:44:06,000 --> 00:44:12,000
If any of these resources is missing any of the six tags,
Config marks it as NON_COMPLIANT.

443
00:44:12,000 --> 00:44:18,000
You can view non-compliant resources with this command.
aws configservice get-compliance-summary-by-config-rule
with config-rule-names finops-required-tags.

444
00:44:18,000 --> 00:44:24,000
You can also set up automatic notifications.
This SNS topic sends an alert to your Slack channel
whenever a non-compliant resource is detected.

445
00:44:24,000 --> 00:44:30,000
aws sns create-topic with name finops-compliance-alerts.

446
00:44:30,000 --> 00:44:36,000
aws sns subscribe with topic ARN and protocol email
and notification endpoint cto at yourcompany.com.

447
00:44:36,000 --> 00:44:42,000
Then attach that SNS topic to Config.
aws configservice put-config-rule with config-rule
finops-required-tags and config-rule-evaluation-mode PROACTIVE.

448
00:44:42,000 --> 00:44:48,000
Proactive mode is the key.
Proactive mode blocks non-compliant resources
before they are created.

449
00:44:48,000 --> 00:44:54,000
If someone tries to create an EC2 instance
without the required tags, the API call fails.

450
00:44:54,000 --> 00:45:00,000
They get an error message telling them
which tags are missing.

451
00:45:00,000 --> 00:45:06,000
No more untagged resources. No more invisible spend.
No more manual cleanup.

452
00:45:06,000 --> 00:45:12,000
Now let's run our first Cost Explorer query
to see the impact of tagging.

453
00:45:12,000 --> 00:45:18,000
This is the command that every FinOps engagement starts with.
I've run this command at over 50 startups.

454
00:45:18,000 --> 00:45:24,000
Every single time, the CTO leans forward
when they see the output.

455
00:45:24,000 --> 00:45:30,000
Why? Because for the first time, they're not looking
at a confusing AWS bill with 47 line items
and usage types they don't understand.

456
00:45:30,000 --> 00:45:36,000
They're looking at a simple table.
Service name. Dollar amount. That's it.

457
00:45:36,000 --> 00:45:42,000
Here's the command.
aws ce get-cost-and-usage with time period Start END.

458
00:45:42,000 --> 00:45:48,000
Granularity MONTHLY. Metrics BlendedCost.
Group-by type DIMENSION, key SERVICE.

459
00:45:48,000 --> 00:45:54,000
Query results by time zero groups with blended cost amount
greater than 10.

460
00:45:54,000 --> 00:46:00,000
Output table.

461
00:46:00,000 --> 00:46:06,000
Let me break down every flag so you understand
what you're running.

462
00:46:06,000 --> 00:46:12,000
Time-period Start dollar sign START, End dollar sign END.
Remember those variables we exported?

463
00:46:12,000 --> 00:46:18,000
START is 30 days ago. END is today.
We're looking at the last 30 days of spend.

464
00:46:18,000 --> 00:46:24,000
Granularity MONTHLY. This tells Cost Explorer
to give us one number per month.

465
00:46:24,000 --> 00:46:30,000
Not per day or per hour.

466
00:46:30,000 --> 00:46:36,000
Metrics BlendedCost. Always use BlendedCost.
It's what you actually pay after Savings Plans,
Reserved Instances, and volume discounts.

467
00:46:36,000 --> 00:46:42,000
Group-by type DIMENSION, key SERVICE.
We're telling AWS to group our costs by service name.

468
00:46:42,000 --> 00:46:48,000
Query. The JMESPath query filters out any service
that costs less than $10 and formats the output as a table.

469
00:46:48,000 --> 00:46:54,000
Output table. Formats the output as a nice ASCII table.

470
00:46:54,000 --> 00:47:00,000
Now run the command.
You should see output that looks like this.

471
00:47:00,000 --> 00:47:06,000
Here is the sample output.

472
00:47:06,000 --> 00:47:12,000
Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud - Compute: $4,230.12.
Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service: $890.45.

473
00:47:12,000 --> 00:47:18,000
Amazon Relational Database Service: $720.33.
Amazon Simple Storage Service: $450.22.

474
00:47:18,000 --> 00:47:24,000
Amazon NAT Gateway: $340.18.
Amazon CloudFront: $210.55.

475
00:47:24,000 --> 00:47:30,000
Amazon EBS: $180.44.
Amazon Route 53: $45.12.
Amazon CloudWatch: $32.88.

476
00:47:30,000 --> 00:47:36,000
Troubleshooting. If you get an error that says
"Invalid time period", check your START and END variables.

477
00:47:36,000 --> 00:47:42,000
Run echo dollar sign START and echo dollar sign END.

478
00:47:42,000 --> 00:47:48,000
If you get "Access denied" or "Unauthorized operation",
your AWS credentials don't have permission to read
Cost Explorer.

479
00:47:48,000 --> 00:47:54,000
If you get nothing, an empty table,
that means your account has zero spend in the last 30 days.

480
00:47:54,000 --> 00:48:00,000
Run aws sts get-caller-identity to confirm which account
you're in.

481
00:48:00,000 --> 00:48:06,000
Now let's interpret the output.
Look at the top service on your list.

482
00:48:06,000 --> 00:48:12,000
For 90 percent of people, it's EC2.
Compute is almost always the biggest line item.

483
00:48:12,000 --> 00:48:18,000
That's normal. That's where you should focus
your optimization efforts first.

484
00:48:18,000 --> 00:48:24,000
Now look at your second and third services.
This is where you find your first opportunities.

485
00:48:24,000 --> 00:48:30,000
If NAT Gateway is in your top five, red flag.
NAT Gateway charges $0.045 per gigabyte for data transfer.

486
00:48:30,000 --> 00:48:36,000
We're going to fix this in Series 2 with VPC Endpoints.

487
00:48:36,000 --> 00:48:42,000
If EKS is high but you only have one cluster,
that's normal. The EKS control plane costs $0.10 per hour.

488
00:48:42,000 --> 00:48:48,000
About $73 per month.

489
00:48:48,000 --> 00:48:54,000
If RDS is high and you have development databases
running 24/7, that's waste.

490
00:48:54,000 --> 00:49:00,000
We'll cover stop and start schedules in Series 2.

491
00:49:00,000 --> 00:49:06,000
If S3 is in your top five, S3 is cheap.
$0.023 per gigabyte.

492
00:49:06,000 --> 00:49:12,000
If you're spending $450 on S3, that's about 20 terabytes.
Do you really have 20 terabytes?

493
00:49:12,000 --> 00:49:18,000
Or do you have lifecycle policies turned off?

494
00:49:18,000 --> 00:49:24,000
Write down your top three services.
Those are your first optimization targets.

495
00:49:24,000 --> 00:49:30,000
Now let's break down cost by region.
This command finds resources running in regions
you don't use.

496
00:49:30,000 --> 00:49:36,000
aws ce get-cost-and-usage with time period Start END.
Granularity MONTHLY. Metrics BlendedCost.

497
00:49:36,000 --> 00:49:42,000
Group-by type DIMENSION, key REGION.
Query results by time zero groups.

498
00:49:42,000 --> 00:49:48,000
Output table.

499
00:49:48,000 --> 00:49:54,000
You'll see something like this.
US East (N. Virginia): $6,230.00.
US West (Oregon): $890.00.
EU (Ireland): $340.00.

500
00:49:54,000 --> 00:50:00,000
If your workloads are supposed to be in us-east-1
but you see cost in us-west-2, someone created resources
in the wrong region.

501
00:50:00,000 --> 00:50:06,000
Here's how to find those stray resources.

502
00:50:06,000 --> 00:50:12,000
For region in us-west-2 eu-west-1 ap-southeast-1.
Do echo "Checking region..." and then aws ec2 describe-instances.

503
00:50:12,000 --> 00:50:18,000
Once you find stray resources, decide.
Migrate them to your primary region. Or delete them.

504
00:50:18,000 --> 00:50:24,000
Or tag them and add them to your regular reporting.
But don't ignore them.

505
00:50:24,000 --> 00:50:30,000
Now let's talk about the 30 to 60 percent savings claim.
Is it real? Can you really save that much?

506
00:50:30,000 --> 00:50:36,000
Or is it marketing hype? Let me show you the math.
Based on real audits across 50 plus startups.

507
00:50:36,000 --> 00:50:42,000
Here is the waste categories table.

508
00:50:42,000 --> 00:50:48,000
Overprovisioned EC2: 25 to 40 percent waste.
Fix: Kubecost rightsizing in Series 3.

509
00:50:48,000 --> 00:50:54,000
gp2 vs gp3 volumes: 20 percent of EBS cost.
Fix: One command migration in Series 2.

510
00:50:54,000 --> 00:51:00,000
Unattached Elastic IPs: $3.65 each per month.
Fix: Release in Series 2.

511
00:51:00,000 --> 00:51:06,000
NAT Gateway traffic: 30 to 50 percent waste.
Fix: VPC Endpoints in Series 2.

512
00:51:06,000 --> 00:51:12,000
RDS overprovisioned: 20 to 30 percent waste.
Fix: Rightsizing in Series 6.

513
00:51:12,000 --> 00:51:18,000
S3 without lifecycle policies: 40 to 60 percent of old data.
Fix: Lifecycle rules in Series 6.

514
00:51:18,000 --> 00:51:24,000
Idle and stopped instances: 5 to 10 percent waste.
Fix: Cleanup in Series 2.

515
00:51:24,000 --> 00:51:30,000
Most startups are wasting 30 to 60 percent of their cloud spend.
Not because they're bad engineers.

516
00:51:30,000 --> 00:51:36,000
Because they set it up once and never looked again.
Cloud is not set and forget.

517
00:51:36,000 --> 00:51:42,000
It's set and continuously optimize.

518
00:51:42,000 --> 00:51:48,000
By the end of Series 2, you will have identified
every dollar of waste in your account.

519
00:51:48,000 --> 00:51:54,000
By the end of Series 4, you will have Karpenter
continuously optimizing your compute.

520
00:51:54,000 --> 00:52:00,000
That's where the big savings live.

521
00:52:00,000 --> 00:52:06,000
Before we end Series 1, you need one more thing.
Your baseline document.

522
00:52:06,000 --> 00:52:12,000
This is the document you'll show your CTO
or your manager.

523
00:52:12,000 --> 00:52:18,000
It proves you know what you're doing.
It shows you've done the work.

524
00:52:18,000 --> 00:52:24,000
And at the end of this course, you'll update it
